run_prompts module

Module containing methods to run prompts on a model.

run_prompts.run_for_scores(prompt_set, filename: str, model_name: str = 'tiiuae/falcon-7b', top_n: int = 10)[source]

Run prompts through a model, where the top_n most likely next tokens and their probabilities are generated for each prompt, then written to a csv file.

Parameters:

  • prompt_set – Dataset of prompts to run through the model.

  • filename – Name of the file to write the scores to.

  • model_name – Name of model to use, must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM. Defaults to Falcon-7B.

  • top_n – The number of words to get the highest probabilities for. Defaults to 10.

run_prompts.run_for_seqs(input_set, output_filename: str, model_name: str = 'tiiuae/falcon-7b', **kwargs)[source]

Run prompts through a model, where sequences are generated for each prompt and written to a file.

Parameters:

  • input_set – Dataset of prompts to run through the model.

  • model_name – Name of model to use, must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM. Defaults to Falcon-7B.

  • kwargs – Keyword arguments to pass to the pipeline function.

Returns:

Output sequences from running the prompts through the model.

run_prompts.test_for_scores(prompt: str, model_name: str = 'tiiuae/falcon-7b', top_n: int = 10)[source]

Run a single prompt through a model and print the top_n most likely next tokens and their probabilities.

Parameters:

  • prompt – Prompt to run through the model.

  • model_name – Name of model to use, must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM. Defaults to Falcon-7B.

  • top_n – The number of words to get the highest probabilities for. Defaults to 10.

run_prompts.test_for_seqs(prompt: str, model_name: str = 'tiiuae/falcon-7b', **kwargs)[source]

Run a single prompt on a model and print the output sequences.

Parameters:

  • prompt – Prompt to run through the model.

  • model_name – Name of model to use, must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM. Defaults to Falcon-7B.

  • kwargs – Keyword arguments to pass to the pipeline function.

helper functions

The above functions are built using these internal helper functions.

run_prompts.get_scores_for_prompt(prompt, model, tokenizer, top_n: int = 10)[source]

For a given prompt, return the top_n most likely next tokens and their probabilities.

Parameters:

  • prompt – The input sequence to get the most likely next tokens for.

  • model – The model to use.

  • tokenizer – The tokenizer to use (should match the model).

  • top_n – The number of words to get the highest probabilities for. Defaults to 10.

Returns:

A list of tuples of the form (word, probability) for the top_n most likely next tokens.

run_prompts.use_pipeline(inp, model_name: str, **kwargs)[source]

Use a pipeline to run a prompt/prompts through a model, returning the output sequences.

Parameters:

  • inp – Input for the pipeline.

  • model_name – Name of model to use, must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM.

  • kwargs – Keyword arguments to pass to the pipeline function.

Returns:

Pipeline object for the specified model.

Load a model and matching tokenizer from HuggingFace.

model_name – Name of the model to load. Must be able to load with AutoModelForCausalLM.

model and tokenizer objects.

run_prompts.write_sequences_out(output_sequences, input_set, filename: str)[source]

Write output sequences to a csv file.

Format: prompt, output_categories, sequence1, sequence2, … sequencen

Parameters:

  • output_sequences – Output sequences to write to file.

  • input_set – PromptSet used to generate the output sequences.

  • filename – Name of the file to write to.

run_prompts.write_scores_out(scores_dict, filename: str)[source]

Take a dictionary of prompts and their top_n most likely tokens with probabilities, and write to a csv file.

Format: prompt, word1, probability1, word2, probability2, …, wordn, probabilityn

Parameters:

  • scores_dict – Dictionary of prompts and their top_n most likely tokens with probabilities

  • filename – Name of file to write to

run_prompts.gen_filename(prefix: str = '', output_dir: str = 'outputs')[source]

Generate a filename for the output file (doesn’t include file extension).

If prefix is specified, filename will start with that prefix and end with a number (e.g. ‘outputs/prefix1’ if no other files with that prefix exist) Otherwise filename will be a number (e.g. ‘outputs/1’ if no other files exist, or ‘outputs/2’ if ‘outputs/1’ already exists, etc)

Parameters:

  • prefix – Prefix to use for the filename. (Optional)

  • output_dir – Directory to save the output file in. Defaults to ‘outputs’. (Optional)

Returns:

Filename to use for the output file, including the directory.
